<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP BEAT: TEEN SCREAMS FOR SHY NEW ORDER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CRAIG LEE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New Order has been together for almost a decade, but the quartet from 
Manchester, England, still has the same testy, sloppy edge of a disgruntled 
post-punk garage band. Maybe that's part of the appeal that packed in all those 
screaming techno-teens on the first of two nights at the Universal Amphitheatre 
on Thursday. Or maybe it was just the striking lighting patterns or the booming 
sequencer patterns that had 'em bouncing. 
</P>
<P>
It can't be stage presence: Peter Hook, resembling a gnarly refugee from an 
German S&amp;M biker club as he pulled dinosaur growls out of his low-slung 
bass, was inappropriately weird, while guitarist/vocalist Bernard Albrecht's 
watery little dance moves and wisp of a voice shouldn't threaten Michael 
Jackson in the near future. But it's this lack of pretension, the vulnerable 
way that a shy, disenfranchised Albrecht struggles to convey a message of 
personal pain above the din of the disco machines in songs like "Perfect Kiss" 
that makes New Order still worth a scream or two. CRAIG LEE 
</P>
</TEXT>
